Transit Oriented Development for Newark & Jersey City, NJ

Chris Michael

September 17, 2022

A. Policy Brief

To,
the City Council Representatives of Newark & Jersey City

Transportation systems have long been considered essential to growth and development in urban regions. Roads, freeways, trains, buses, and trams form the backbone of cities across the world by providing a network to connect people with jobs and housing, and enabling the movement of goods and capital. They create a way for people to earn an income, access amenities, and consume goods and services. By the very nature and purpose of transportation systems, it can be assumed that they would have a positive impact on economic mobility. Yet, to what extent do households value transit-rich neighborhoods compared to others?

This study aims to look at the effect Transit Oriented Development (TOD) has had on urban growth in the cities of Newark and Jersey City between 2009 and 2019. The data for this study was obtained at the county level from the American Community Survey and the New Jersey Geographic Information Network (NJGIN) Open Data portal. The primary focus of this study will be centered around the Newark Light Rail (operating in Essex County), and the HudsonBergen Light Rail (operating in Hudson County). Three key takeaways have been identified and analysed in an attempt to understand what they mean for the cities and counties as a whole.

There has been a larger increase in population in TOD areas compared to non-TOD areas over the years

There has been an 8.6% increase in the population living in TOD areas, and a 1.7% increase in the population living in non-TOD areas in the two counties over the decade. This growth could be attributed to a larger portion of the population choosing to live in close proximity to transit stations for commute to work and for easier access to urban amenities. The percent of white population has remained relatively unchanged in TOD regions, while the percent of black population decreased by 17.2%. Both racial groups saw a decrease in population in non-TOD regions. It can be difficult to determine what causes these changes- could be ageing in place, change in demographics, or simple migration in search of better job opportunities.

There has been a greater increase in rent in non-TOD areas compared to TOD areas over the years

There has been a 32.5% increase in rent in non-TOD areas between 2009-2019. TOD areas saw a slightly smaller increase of 26.7% in the same time frame. This increase in rent has been accompanied by an increase in median household income in both regions. However, in non-TOD areas, the increase in median household income (+21.4%) is not in line with the 33% increase in rent over the years. This could imply a decrease in affordability as we move away from transit infrastructure. This can also be linked to the 12.2% increase in poverty in non-TOD areas. The increase in rent in both regions could also price out residents who cannot continue to afford the costs of living in these areas.

There has been an increase in the proportion of educated popuation in TOD areas over the years

There has been a 10.6% increase in the number of people with a bachelors degree living in TOD areas, and a decrease of 20.6% in the same category in non-TOD areas. This could imply that educated people value proximity to TOD regions, and could potentially be willing to pay to be closer to transit rich neighborhoods. The decrease in poverty (-3.3%) in TOD areas can also imply an increase in purchasing power of the residents. There seems to be a greater shift in demographics in non-TOD areas compared to TOD areas which could be a combination of multiple factors which are outside the scope of this study.

Concluding thoughts

From this preliminary analysis, it can be difficult to say that households value transit-rich neighborhoods and are willing to pay for proximity to these regions. There are multiple factors that affect demographic and household shifts over time. Presence of public transit infrastructure along with pedestrian and bike accessibility have to be considered while analyzing the difference between TOD and non-TOD neighborhoods. In addition to that, mode of commute to work, type of employment sector, presence of school districts, access to food and healthcare options are all important factors that affect household formation in a region. For a future study, layering various indicators over public transit infrastructure may help us better understand the benefits of Transit Oriented Development.

                        "B06012_002E", "B02001_003E"), 
          year=2009, state=34, county=017, 
          geometry=TRUE, output="wide") %>%
  rename(TotalPop = B25026_001E, 
         Whites = B02001_002E,
         TBlacks = B02001_003E,
         FemaleBachelors = B15001_050E, 
         MaleBachelors = B15001_009E,
         MedHHInc = B19013_001E,

         pctBlack = ifelse (TotalPop > 0, TBlacks / TotalPop, 0),
         pctBachelors = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, ((FemaleBachelors + MaleBachelors) / TotalPop),0),
         pctPoverty = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, TotalPoverty / TotalPop, 0),

  dplyr::select(-Whites, -FemaleBachelors, -MaleBachelors, -TotalPoverty)

III. Spatial Selection Techniques

The 3 spatial selections techiques used in this section are __clip__, __spatial_selection__ and __centroid__. All three techiques are plotted, however the centroid technique will be used extensively throughout this assignment because it does not alter the geometries of the census tracts during selection.

sf::sf_use_s2(FALSE)

clip <- st_intersection(buffer, tracts09) %>%
  dplyr::select(TotalPop) %>%
  mutate(Selection_Type = "by Clip")

selection <- tracts09 %>% 
  st_join(buffer, join = st_intersects) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(Legend)) %>% 
  dplyr::select(TotalPop) %>%
  mutate(Selection_Type = "by Spatial Intersects")

centroids <- st_centroid(tracts09)[buffer,] %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>% 
  left_join(., dplyr::select(tracts09, GEOID), by = "GEOID") %>%
  st_sf() %>%
  dplyr::select(TotalPop) %>%
  mutate(Selection_Type = "by Centroids")

centroids2 <- st_centroid(tracts09)[buffer,] %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>% 
  left_join(., dplyr::select(tracts09, GEOID), by = "GEOID") %>%
  st_sf() %>%
  dplyr::select(MedRent) %>%
  mutate(Selection_Type = "by Centroids")

intersections <- rbind(clip, selection, centroids)
ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data=intersections, aes(fill = q5(TotalPop))) +
  geom_sf(data=NJ_Stops) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = col5,
                    labels = qBr(intersections, "TotalPop"),
                    name = "\nTotal Population\n(Quintile Breaks)") +

  labs(title="3 Spatial Selection Techniques",

       caption="\nSource: NJGIN Open Data") +

D. Developing TOD Indicators

I. TOD Time-Space Groups

sf::sf_use_s2(FALSE)

allTracts.group <- 
  rbind(st_centroid(allTracts)[buffer,] %>%
      st_drop_geometry() %>%
      left_join(allTracts) %>%
      st_sf() %>%
      mutate(TOD = "TOD"),
    st_centroid(allTracts)[buffer, op = st_disjoint] %>%
      st_drop_geometry() %>%
      left_join(allTracts) %>%
      st_sf() %>%
      mutate(TOD = "Non-TOD")) %>%
  mutate(MedRent.inf = ifelse(year == "2009", MedRent * 1.19, MedRent)) %>%
  mutate(MedHHInc.inf=ifelse(year == "2009", MedHHInc * 1.19, MedHHInc))

cola <-   adjustcolor( "black", alpha.f = 0.3)

sf::sf_use_s2(FALSE)

NJ_Coords <- ("+proj=tmerc +lat_0=38.83333333333334 +lon_0=-74.5 +k=0.9999 +x_0=150000 +y_0=0 +ellps=GRS80 +datum=NAD83 +to_meter=0.3048006096012192 +no_defs ")

NJ_Stops_2 <- st_read("C:/Users/Chris Michael/Desktop/UPenn/Fall 2022/508/MUSA_508_Lab-main/MUSA_508_Lab-main/Week_2/Light_Rail_Stations_of_NJ_Transit.geojson")%>%st_transform(st_crs(NJ_Coords))%>%
  filter(COUNTY %in% c ("Hudson","Essex"))

                                maxDistance = 63360,

  st_transform(st_crs(NJ_Coords))

The multiple ring buffers were created at 1/2 mile intervals and were used to plot the graph of rent as a function of distance- to visualize the changes in median rent as we move further away from TOD zones.

ggplot() +

II. Plotting Rent vs.Distance to the Light Rail

sf::sf_use_s2(FALSE)

NJ_Buffer_2 <- multipleRingBuffer(st_union(NJ_Stops_2),
                                maxDistance = 63360,
                                interval =  2640) %>%
  st_transform(st_crs(tracts19))


MRB_1 <- st_join(NJ_Buffer_2, tracts19, by = "geometry")%>%
  dplyr::mutate(MedRent_19 = MedRent)%>%
  select(c('distance','GEOID','MedRent_19','geometry'))%>%
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>% 
  replace(is.na(.), 0)

MRB_A = MRB_1 %>% group_by(distance)  %>%
                    summarise(MedRent_19 = mean(MedRent_19))


MRB_2 <- st_join(NJ_Buffer_2, tracts09, by = "geometry")%>%
  dplyr::mutate(MedRent_09 = MedRent*1.19)%>%
  select(c('distance','GEOID','MedRent_09','geometry'))%>%
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>% 
  replace(is.na(.), 0)

MRB_B = MRB_2 %>% group_by(distance)  %>%
                    summarise(MedRent_09 = mean(MedRent_09))

MRB <- full_join(MRB_A, MRB_B, by = "distance") %>%
  drop_na()
ggplot(data = MRB, aes(x = distance)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = MedRent_19), color = "#af5d4c", size = 1, show.legend = TRUE)+
  geom_point(aes(y = MedRent_19), color = "#af5d4c", size = 3)+
  geom_line(aes(y = MedRent_09), color="#899da4", size = 1, show.legend = TRUE)+
  geom_point(aes(y = MedRent_09), color = "#899da4", size = 3)+
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Distance",
                     limits = c(2640, 63360),
                     breaks = seq(2640, 63360, by=5280),
                     labels = c("0.5mi","1.5mi","2.5mi","3.5mi","4.5mi","5.5mi",
                                "6.5mi","7.5mi","8.5mi","9.5mi","10.5mi","11.5mi"))+
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Average Rent (in 2019 dollars)",
                     limits = c(700,3100),
                     breaks = seq(700,3100, by=450),
                     labels = c ("$700","$1,150","$1,600","$2,050","$2,500","$2,950"))+
  labs(title = "Rent as a function of Distance from Light Rail Stations",
       subtitle="Hudson & Essex County, New Jersey", 
       caption="Source: NJGIN Open Data") +
   scale_color_manual(name='Year',
                     breaks=c('2019', '2009'),
                     values=c('2019'='#af5d4c', '2009'='#899da4'))+
  theme_minimal()

The rent values have been adjusted for inflation. The analysis of the graph will exclude the two outliers in the 2019 data. From the graph, the median rent seems to decrease as we move away from the TOD zones, but begins to climb again after a certain distance (2.5 miles). The rent seems to continue to climb as the distance increase, which could imply a hike in housing prices as we move into the suburbs. The rent values start to drop again after 9.5 miles and then becomes constant after 11 miles from the TOD zones. These areas could be seeing fewer newer developments compared to regions closer to public transit, and do not offer as many incentives for residents to move to the area.
